<HEADLINE>
FT  20 NOV 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Surge of late buying restores
Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ANOTHER big rise in bond yields initially pushed US share prices lower
yesterday, but a surge of late buying related to the expiration of stock
options and futures contracts helped blue-chip stocks end the day on an
upbeat note, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average up 8.67 at 3,694.01, more
than 30 points above its low for the day. The more broadly based Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 ended 1.02 lower at 462.60, while the Amex composite finished
down 1.56 at 467.98, and the Nasdaq composite off 2.78 at 751.56. Trading
volume on the NYSE was 300m shares.
US stock markets ended a difficult week in mixed form. Although fear that
the House of Representatives would reject Nafta gave way to relief at its
comfortable passage on Wednesday night, the steady rise in long-term
interest rates meant that any celebration was short-lived.
Once again bond prices were in retreat. This time it was a combination of
economic news - rising imports and exports in September widened the monthly
trade deficit to Dollars 10.9bn - and heavy selling of Treasury-bond futures
that undermined bonds. By late afternoon the benchmark 30-year bond was down
1 1/4 points, and the yield was up to 6.33 per cent, the highest level since
mid-August.
The rise in bond yields upset stocks, which posted steady declines
throughout the morning. At one stage the Dow was down almost 30 points.
Prices gradually recovered, however, and thanks to heavy late buying related
to the expiration of stock and stock index futures and options, the leading
average finished in positive territory. Several leading Dow constituents
posted declines, although most recovered some of their losses late in the
day. United Technologies fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 62 7/8 , Caterpillar
dropped Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 85, and IBM gave up Dollars  7/8 at Dollars
51 7/8 . Bank stocks were under pressure because of rising long-term
interest rates. Citicorp eased Dollars 1 to Dollars 34, JP Morgan gave up
Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 69 1/2 , Chemical fell Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 36
7/8 and Wells Fargo slipped Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 115 1/8 .
Chevron, which fell sharply on Thursday on the news that Pennzoil had sold
almost half its stake in the company, rebounded Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 89
7/8 .
General Mills fell Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 61 1/2 after the broking house,
Dean Witter Reynolds, cut its earnings estimate, citing the intense
competitive environment in the food business. In spite of the markets'
weakness, retailer Talbots made a successful debut. Floated at Dollars 19.50
a share, the stock ended at Dollars 22 5/8 in volume of 6.8m shares. On the
Nasdaq market, Ornda Healthcorp fell Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 12 1/2 after
the company said it would merge with American Healthcare Management in a
deal valued at Dollars 400m.
Canada
TORONTO share prices posted a small gain in moderate trading. The composite
index was up 3.43 points, or 0.08%, to close at 4238.17, a loss on the week
of about 65 points.
